title: Transformers Unicron Short Display Base Stand

description.text:
The Transformers Armada Unicron toy was designed to sit horizontally on a table, but can't stand on its own vertically. I designed this stand to allow it to both display in the vertical profile. This is the second stand I designed, the first stand requires a steel rod to support the figure at a higher profile.

All components of this stand can be printed, no other materials are needed. This stand will hold Unicron just above the surface of the display base. The arms are designed to intersect the holder at the balance point, so that it won't be front or back heavy while being displayed.

The images attached are from a print at .2mm layer height. To get a smoother layer transition around the ring in the base, print at a .15 or .1 layer height instead.

I printed this with 15% infill, and it's working fine, but increasing the infill will also increase the rigidity of the arms and the holder that Unicron rests on. The holder must be printed using support. Printing the holder in the orientation provided will leave the less smooth side with the supports hidden on the top, where the figure rests. You can also rotate the holder 90 degrees, onto its side, where the support will only appear along one edge. This makes the support look clean on both top and bottom, but takes twice as long to print.

For long-term display, I would suggest gluing the arms into the base and holder before using it. The slots for the arms are designed to tightly fit the base and holder, but they could loosen over time without being glued together.

I printed the stand pictured in PLA Plus. PLA/PLA Plus is the recommended material for the rigidity it gives to the holder, where most of the figure's weight is balanced. PETG might work, but would also have slightly more flexibility.

description.text: These ultra low profile rotational mounts are designed for the most demanding of applications where space is at a premium. Typical applications are for waveplates and polarisers in a laser system. One mount accepts a 5x5 mm optic up to 3 mm thick and the other takes a standard 0.5" circular optic up to 2 mm thick - use a little spot of epoxy to hold the optic in place and you're good to go! Both have a beam height of 0.4625" (11.784 mm) in order to be used seamlessly with Siskiyou mirror mounts (we used their IXF.50TA mounts). The top of these mounts capture an M2 nut so that an M2x6 screw can secure the mount in place after rotation. Bonus: if you use nylon nuts and screws the whole mount is completely non-magnetic. Nice!

Glue your optic in place with a couple of spots of epoxy in the pockets within the model and allow these to fully cure before assembling. Try to make sure you keep the optic as flat as possible when you glue it in. Press an M2 nut into the rectangular hole the the top of the mount - it should only fit when oriented flat-to-flat (this stops it rotating when in use). Add an M2x6 screw through the top hole of the mount and you're ready to go! Protip: Print the retaining ring pieces in different colours for polarisers and waveplates so you know what they are at a glance.

description.text:
Inspired by Bit holder by mattbeechan.

Unfortunately v1 had some major issues (I did not properly test :S ). The v2 was tested more thoroughly and I added a few nice features (such as the tightness control and the added magnet feature). If you should run into any kind of problem, please let me know in the comments.

This model is highly customizable (see section "What is customizable"). There are also a few examples added for inspiration.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.4x0.2

Infill:

50%

Notes:

Rather easy to print. For fast print high infill is recommended. Support might be necessary (see "What is customizable?").

What is customizable?
  • Number of hexagonal indentations for the bits in x- and y-direction.
  • Spacing between these indentations in x- and y-direction. For nice rows I recommend values of more than 3mm in the y- and -1 in the x-direction (negative values will connect the hexagonal shapes).
  • Depth of the indentations for the bits (how deep will the bit go into the holder). I advise a value between 6 and 10mm.
  • Thickness of the connecting bottom layer/baseplate.
  • Width of the skirt into the four directions. Good for drilling additional holes for fixing the bitholder to something else, holding it down while retrieving a bit or labelling rows/columns of bits.
  • Thickness of the walls around the bits. The wider the more stable. Also consider your nozzle-/print-width.
  • Tightness in percent. 0 is very loose, 100% is very tight! You might have to play around with this a little. Don't forget, that the tightness will decrease over time.
  • You can also (alternatively) add a circular hole for a magnet at the bottom of the baseplate, that will keep the bits in place and/or the bitholder on a magnetic surface. You can specify depth and diameter of your magnet. Don't forget to add a little print tolerance! If your magnet is thinner than your baseplate, there will be some suspended baseplate left. Its thickness controls the force that keeps the bits in place. Don't make it too thin though (will be hard to print. Also consider to use support for larger radii). If you don't want to add magnets, set to zero.
"FAQ" or "Problems you might run into"
  • Some values/parameters will automatically be limited to values that still produce a non-degenerate output, this range is usually indicated in square brackets. If nothing happens, you might be outside these boundaries.
  • Don't forget, that you might have to turn your model in the preview to look at the bottom in order to see the holes for the magnets ;)

This is an example of leaf gilding.  In contrast to gold color paint, this print is covered with a layer of actual gold so thin you can see the layer lines through it.  The process is easy to learn, but difficult to master.  Total retail cost of the gold was about US$1.  
This process dates back at least to Ancient Egypt, so it seems fitting to combine it with the latest of manufacturing techniques.

description.text:
I modified this to mount on the left side of Anet AM8 frame and also be able to swivel. Being on the left side it could interfere with the x axis stepper motor depending on the angle you have the screen and the height it is mounted and the height of your print. So BEWARE of this.

The holes for the base are M5, and the hinges are M3.

I have not printed this yet, but will in the next few weeks.

Edit 8/16/17 - I redid the hinges to make them easier to print for people with less than perfect bed adhesion. Printed it out and have it fitted to my AM8. The M5 holes are a little tight and the M3 holes in the hinge are loose, but they both have about the same tolerance in the model. So my printer calibration is probably off a bit. I'm using thumb wheel nuts for the hinges so I can swivel the screen and lock them into position.

title: Anet A8 Z Axis Leveling Tool

description.text:
I designed this as a fast printing tool to level the Z Axis steppers specifically for the Anet A8 as the only tool I could find was too short to use on my machine. Simply slip the tool over the Y Axis 8mm rod on one side and wind the stepper down til it rests on the top of the tool. Repeat for the other side and both steppers will be equal. Better yet - it's such a quick print, just print 2 of them and do both sides at the same time for better, easier and faster levelling.

In the picture you can see I'm using 2 of them, and I use the back of the bed to make sure they're both in line with each other for best accuracy.

If your steppers have gotten out of alignment you may need to re-level your bed after you level the steppers as well.

This is my very first design so I'd really like to hear any and all feedback - Thanks!

Printer:

Anet A8

description.text:
I integrated a raspberry pi inside of the CR-10 electronics case.

Instructions

  • Cut a 54mm x 20mm hole 11mm from the top and 40mm from the back of the case.
  • Epoxy pi mount in place. It's should be 20mm from the side wall where the hole is cut and about 38mm from the back inner wall. Tip: attach the pi to the mount, and then epoxy the mount, this will make sure everything is properly aligned and the additional weight will help to hold the mount in place while the epoxy dries.
  • Epoxy the IO cover to the outside of the case. The top of the cover should be 9mm from the top of the case and 32mm from the back of the case. Tip: It is easier to position this with the pi in place.

In addition to the raspberry pi mount there is a mount for a single channel relay and a LM2596 DC-DC adapter with spacers to mount it above the raspberry pi.

The pi is powered from the 12V power supply using the LM2596 and using the relay to toggle power to the CR-10 main board. The rear exhaust fan was, replaced with a quieter fan, and rewired to be powered on independently of the main board so that it runs as long as the power supply is switched on. The front fan still powers on with the main board.

Note: If you just want to integrate the raspberry pi and power it with independently the power supply cable can be put through the existing cable grommet.

Note: The raspberry pi is placed directly over the cable tie mount. The mount will still be usable after installation the wires will just have to be run under the pi.

Links to parts used.
LM2596:
https://www.amazon.com/RioRand-LM2596-Converter-1-23V-30V-1Pcs-LM2596/dp/B008BHAOQO

Single channel relay:
https://www.amazon.com/Tolako-Arduino-Indicator-Channel-Official/dp/B00VRUAHLE

Rear fan replacement
https://www.amazon.com/Noctua-Cooling-Blades-Bearing-NF-A4x10/dp/B009NQLT0M

As for screws: I used the screws that held the old thicker exhaust fan to mount everything as they were the perfect length. To mount the new fan I used some M3x12mm screws that I had around.

title: No Man's Sky Portal- Variant I

description.text:
This model is intended to be a test for another iteration in the later future. If you would like, please send this model to your printer, and tell me how it looks. If everything goes well I will release a more detailed model to the market, as well as make it available for sale on Shapeways. If not, I will make the changes necessary.

I do not recommend attempting to print this object at more than 4 inches tall, simply due to time and plastic requirements. I also recommend using a reinforced hollow build structure available through most printers, for the same reason.

The No Man's Sky Portal Statue is intended to be a small trophy or statuette, perfect for displaying in your home or at the office. It features the portal altar, a baseplate for stability, and a "golden orb" (a cheeky reference to the days when players thought pushing the orbs found at portals into the altar would activate it).

Why am I making this?

After the successful conclusion of the Waking Titan ARG (Created by the A&S Company in collaboration with Hello Games), it was announced that 10,000 physical copies of the Atlas V4 Pass would be shipped to random participants for no additional charge. However, more than a quarter of a million people participated in the ARG. This trophy, once finalized, will be available to anyone who wants it, specifically those that do not receive an Atlass V4 Pass or were otherwise unable to participate. It is an alternative reward for your work in Waking Titan.

It was also a unique and fun way for me to get back into Blender, the 3d software I used to create this Portal, working closely with Booleans to carve shapes into the model.

Earliest rendition (No baseplate, stone steps on one side, no carvings) Second Iteration (Baseplate with golden ball, stones surround pillar, carvings) Third Iteration (Smaller Baseplate, moved ball)

description.text:
This is a rocket from my youth. You print it, put some vinegar in the tube, wad up a bit of baking soda (arm and hammer brand works best). Stuff the wad into the end of the rocket, and stick the base onto it (while the rocket is still pointing at the ground. When you turn it over, the vinegar mixed with the powder and after a few seconds the rocket shoot up into the air,
in the tube there also has to be some air-space, otherwise it will not compress the air and your lift is not so high.

These are some hubstacks based on the kind that come on yoyos such as the MagicYoyo K1 and K3. They are my favorite shape, so I based these VERY closely on them.

They can sometimes print a little bit too wide, I have printed 4 so far, two in each orientation that I uploaded, and 1/4 was too loose-fitting, so you may have to ever so slightly modify it, or shim it with a piece of paper or something. I think if it were narrowed by .1mm in width and depth, that could possibly make it work every time, but I haven't had time to try that yet.

They are best printed with the bearing side (the narrower side) facing up. The wider side facing up ended up having some random stringing going on inside of them, and I had to dig them out with a small screwdriver, but they still worked. I have included two files, so that you may print them however you choose.

Have fun!

author: kingzen

title: Eachine E010(S) TX04 Camera Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Eachine TX04 Camera Holder for the Eachine E010 frame

A Camera Holder for the Eachine TX04 camera (FPV) to be mounted between the ducts of the Eachine E010 quadrocopter frame. (The E010 / E010S / E010E are all the same frames)
The angle at which the camera is mounted can be configured freely, in the pictures i use a 5° mount.
This is meant to be printed on a FDM printer with PLA filament and it weighs 0.2 grams.

The goal is to mount the camera as protected as possible and as center as possible on the frame, while allowing for different camera angles. For this the Eachine TX04 camera is seemingly perfect, the boards are separable while the camera module itself is as small as possible.

Note that the camera will show a little bit of the frame ducts in the picture, but it is really only a very small part of the picture.

PLEASE READ THE FOLLOWING

This is a very challenging print:

  • You will need skills in printing, soldering, cutting, gluing and overall handling small parts
  • If your printer strings the cleanup can take a lot of time
  • Everything you will handle is incredibly small
  • The camera can be easily destroyed if you are not careful enough (The camera has SMD parts that are smaller than a millimeter!)
  • Soldering the wires is challenging in itself, you will need a very fine soldering tip (Max. 1mm)
  • The transmitter board needs to be attached between the battery holder and the controller board
  • Everything needs to be mounted backwards on the frame since the bar that is used to attach the camera is on the backside of the frame
  • Please check if your board can be mounted backwards BEFORE you do anything else. (My E010S board works perfectly backwards). If yours does not fit backwards i suggest buying the "Eachine Beecore F3_EVO_Brushed (has no telemetry)" or the "ACROWHOOP V2" board instead.

What to do

  1. First you need the holder itself, it is a fast 9 minute print in fine print quality.
  2. Clean any stringing up, take special care of the parts that grip the frame itself, since they are overhangs which cannot be printed with support your printer will most likely print 1 or 2 layers of garbage there, you have to clean up the groove with a scalpel or other fine knife
  3. Try on the holder onto the camera lens, you should be able to bend it open to snap it over the neck of your lens
  4. The lens clips should grab directly under the widest part of the lens, if the spacing is off change the corresponding setting in the OpenSCAD file and re-print the holder
  5. Now try to attach the holder to the frame itself, it should be a tight fit while not bending the frame bar too much, if it does not fit correctly change the corresponding setting in the OpenSCAD file and re-print the holder
  6. Separate both boards of the camera carefully with "Flush Cutters", DO NOT use normal thick wire cutters, they smush the material more than really cutting anything, alternatively you can de-solder the pins holding the two boards together
  7. Cut off the upper lip (The one with two solder pins, NOT the one with three solder pins) extending off the camera board like shown on one of the pictures above, again best use Flush Cutters here
  8. Solder a 3-wire cable between both boards in the length you need (Something around 2.5 cm, don't cut them too short), BE CAREFUL of the order of the wires, otherwise you fry your camera!
  9. Attach the camera to the frame as shown above, glue the transmitter board on top of the battery compartment with double sided tape, or if you are adventurous try hot glue (Although the transmitter gets pretty hot)
  10. Re-attach your motors and your controller board BACKWARDS. That means that the new "forward" is now pointing to the original "backwards" side of the frame. Your controller board will only attach with 3 screws. To attach the controller board it can be a good idea to use anti-vibration rubber stand-offs, you can get them from Banggod if you search for "E010S"

I destroyed My copter / My camera / My fingers / My whatever, what now?

I am sorry to say it, but you are on your own. I will and cannot give any guarantees or further help at all.
Ye have been warned!

Have fun tinkering!

description.text:
This is a night light base, it fits a custom made RGB leds controlled by a arduino mini pro and a rotary encode with a push button. (Yep overkill, but it's what I had laying around)

I used these arduinos and encoder:
https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B007YQZUEE/ref=ox_sc_act_title_1?smid=A1NBUX8FDB1DWX&psc=1
https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B0085I4D5C/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

But any should work.

Turning the the encoder controls brightness, pushing it cycles the colors, at the moment the cycle is {off, white, red, green, blue, magenta, cyan, yellow};

Arduino code included, pinouts are in the code.
Leds are fully addressable type, I just cut 3 off some leftover ones from another project, usually these are sold in 2-3m runs, something like this: https://www.adafruit.com/product/1138

For the power supply I just cut a regular USB cable used the red and black (5V and GND) and plugged that in the Arduino. For this amount of leds any USB brick should work, with 3 LED's it uses up a maximum of 140mA, but at night light levels it usually used around 40mA (it's very bright at full power).

The idea is to put a hollow figure on top like the one pictured: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1912559

Made it for my son, and he wanted the option to remove the figure, to take it to school, etc.

I will print/make a knob at some point, it's harder for me to rotate it than for me son so it wasn't a priority.

Enjoy.

description.text:
After breaking my original 3D Systems CubeX Duo touch screen I discovered a solution to a major issue with this printer. This printer has a sticker ( Photos 2 and 3) as the force against the touch screen sensor. Over time the glue gets less sticky and the force needed to keep pressure on the sensor is no longer there. I designed a plastic face to press force upon the sensor to make it work with out issue.

NOTE: If you have never removed the sticker before take it slowly because the touch sensor may stick to the sticker. Take your time to remove the sticker from the touch screen so you don't break it. If done correctly the sticker should look like (Photo 2) with no gold frame. If there is a gold frame you need to carefully remove it and place the + and - on the gold frame upon the screen. If you want a step by step walk through fill free to comment or email me at [email protected] I'd be happy to help.

remixed_from.author: Bryceletarmo
remixed_from.title: Fixe Spanner for Bowden Extruder - Tarantula (and Other)

description.text:
I'll be perfectly honest... I don't know jack about extruders, I just know that the gap present in the original model, between the gears, seemed like it could be improved. So, I did. I hope... lol

Now, I can take a piece of bent PLA or ABS and feed it through with no jamming, as long as I get it inside the curved portion of the bearing. It then goes right in the hole, no issues. I did drill it out the hole where the filament feeds through with a 5/64 or 1.90 mm drill bit that I had on hand.

I think this would work well for changing filaments mid print. Time will tell. Please let me know if you encounter any issues. Thanks!

Oh, after you first install it, pull the levers apart slightly, so that the bearing presses into the plastic, this will let the extruder bite better into the filament.

Printer:

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
I made this portable dice tower because I wanted a simple, elegant tool for game night. No more game board disruptions from enthusiastic rolls! I included the files so you could two-color print some proper 16mm dice as an added bonus. If you don't have a two-head printer, you can print the single die and add color with a dice marker.

The dice in the picture are 15mm single-color dice with a dice marker used to add the color. A dice marker is basically a giant crayon used to scrape wax into the holes in the die. I gave someone the 16mm dice and I only had my original 15mm dice for the photo.

title: Bronto Bracket - Prusa MK2s / MK3 Filament Guide (V2)

description.text:
I designed this filament guide to serve as an anchor point for a 4mm PTFE tube running from a filament drybox to clamp directly to the center of the top of the frame of my Prusa i3 MK2S.

V2 adds a riser for the PTFE port, so it won't hit the extruder at maximum height. That isn't really an issue for 99% of prints, but it tends to be if you raise your Z to the top for maintenance tasks (don't ask me how I know).

There are three versions of the file:
M10 - This one has a threaded hole to accept a PC4-M10 Male Straight Pneumatic PEFE Tube Push Connector

Also included a version with custom supports because it's difficult to add supports with most programs that won't add supports to the M10 threads.

4mm Hole - This one just has a 4mm hole you can use to shove your PTFE tube into, or you could use this one as a normal filament guide
Solid - Not sure why anyone would want this, but you could theoretically print it and drill your own filament holes in it should you desire to do so

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Resolution:

0.15- mm for threaded version

Infill:

20%

Notes:

For V2, you should print on its side and hope your printer is calibrated well enough to give you a round hole.

Legacy instructions for V1

Which version you want will warrant different print orientations / settings.

I'd recommend printing the threaded version with the threaded end on the bed, so you guarantee the hole is round. I'd recommend a high enough resolution to ensure the threads are printed (I did 0.15 mm but I don't know what all resolutions would work with M10-1.0 threads).

If you print it standing up, you probably need supports unless your printer is magic. Mine is not, don't ask me how I know.

Print one of everything except for the bases, those you'll want to print multiples of so you can swap out miniatures for assembly line painting. I use blue poster tack to stick the mini to the bases.

You'll need at least 2 of these magnets from K&J (or wherever). Put a dab of super glue in the hole of the main body (its up underneath as shown in the picture). Place a magnet in there. Next, put a dab of glue in one of the bases, set it atop the main body with the hole facing up, and drop a magnet in there. These magnets are CRAZY strong, so be careful! Pull the base off and continue until all bases have a magnet.

Glue the finger grip into the slot of the main body. Its a pretty snug fit from my ultimaker, so it should stay in well until the glue sets. I didn't glue the handle extender in just in case I wanted to change the style or length of it, instead using a large blob of blue poster tack.

Happy painting!

print_settings.Notes:: The infill doesn't matter much unless you're making a thick-walled jig, and the resolution can also be just about anything as long as the course steps don't impede the movement of the drill through the jig.  When fine-tuning the hole size with the fudge_factor, you want a snug fit around the drill bit so the alignment is maintained during drilling, but not so tight that the friction generates heat and softens the plastic while you use it.

description.text:
This parametric angled edge drill jig is to help drill holes in the edge of a material in any defined alignment. I created it to help with working on a set of rocket fins. In this case, I needed to cut a tab off the fins to allow them to pass through my fin beveling jig, so I made this hole jig to drill an angled hole through the fins before cutting off the tabs to allow for perfect alignment when gluing the tabs back on as well as added strength in the joint. This jig could be used for any case when a hole needs to be drilled into the edge of a part, and the angle is configurable.
To aid with alignment of the jig, a raised bump is on one side of the jig to show exactly where the hole will be. The fudge_factor variable in the scad file lets you fine tune the hole size to compensate for filament shrinkage, over-extrusion, etc.

bryden42 had a great idea with their X-wing card and token holder, but I saw some room for improvement. I've also included the 123d Design file in case anyone wants to make further adjustments.

Happy gaming!

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/el4xkGuq25f

See the hole I put in the bottom of the more complicated piece? The handle should fit in it. Apply model cement to all inside surfaces of the hole and the top of the handle, stick the end of the handle in the hole and hold the parts together for at least ten seconds to let the glue start to dry.
We use our Makerbot Replicator so much that we began needing several SD cards to keep up with demand. This started looking a bit messy, so we used the printer itself to fix the problem. Nice!

Print the model then remove the screw on the lower right of the Makerbot front panel. Push this screw through the hole in the caddy and reattach it to the Makerbot. There is a tab on the right hand side which will prevent the caddy from rotating (although it seems that the force from the screw is more than enough to stop this from happening anyway). V1: This version has a thick back plate (2 mm) and requires the stock M6x8 screw to be replaced with M6x10 screw in order to mount to the Replicator. V2: This version has a thinner back plate (0.8 mm) that will hopefully allow the stock M6x6 screw to mount this to the Replicator (let us know if this works!).

This isn't really a remix, but more of an addon to Jabberwock's Star Wars X-wing: 3-D asteroid bases. I liked those bases but didn't have ready access to lava rocks, plus I wanted something that matched the shape of the bases when viewed from above, so I modeled these. Each asteroid has 2 files, one is just the straight export, and the oriented one is what meshmixer spit out as the best orientation for support material purposes. I recommend using the oriented version with supports and a raft or brim. After printing these and Jabberwock's bases, I then covered the asteroids in PVA glue (aka school glue) and play sand to give them a more rocky texture. I then primed them with a zenithal method (video tutorial here, I used rattle can primer from walmart). Then used some thin paints of various colors to give them some diversity (though I think I may redo some of them), and there ya go!

Happy gaming!

title: Improved Pen Spring Double Action OTF SwitchBlade

description.text:
This is a remixed version of "Pen Spring DA OTF Knife" by "davinci85" with an edited blade that's still blunt and safe, but looks more aesthetically pleasing. I also added "teeth" to the switch so you can get a better grip with your thumb.

FINAL: (Lol) Added a new blade that's still blunt and not pointy but looks even better. Made the latch stronger, and also made the bumps on the case more dramatic so the SwitchBlade can now snap together without glue and can easily taken apart with a knife or tool.

Final (Hopefully): (Feb. 8th, 2018) I printed, and redesigned many, many times and I got it working. I believe I pretty much have the best design changes I can make to this. To insert the pen spring, start at the middle of the grove where it is slightly wider. Push in one end of the spring and drag it to it's end while pushing in more from the back of the spring. Compress the rest to push in the other end of the spring to it's place from the middle. It will be a bit of a tight fit, just be careful.

Edit: (Sept. 24th, 2017) I have just printed this and am still running into multiple problems. So if you want to save filament, please wait until I fix these issues. I only have a couple to go. I will let you guys know when with one more edit to the description here when I'm done.
P.S. My printer isn't functioning properly now so it will be a little longer now. :/

EDIT!!: As of September 18th, 2017, all parts have been improved and modified, along with a few new changes.

  1. I have checked and fixed/made sure that everything is sized properly and fits better together as I had to sand parts down to size so they could fit. I don't know if anyone else had problems with that but I did. Please note that you still have to sand the parts smooth regardless to reduce friction.

  2. I have added spacers to the top half of the case so it is not possible to glue the 2 halves together too tight. (So the mechanism is just loose enough to function nicely.)

  3. The part where the spring sits on the blade has little cutouts so its easier to put the spring in, but has remaining extended ledges that jut out to prevent the spring from popping out while using. This is especially helpful for stronger/longer/stretched pen springs. Please take a look at the picture of it above to see what I mean.

  4. The teeth on the switch have been enlarged.

title: Total Eclipse pendant
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Want to celebrate the 2017 Total Solar Eclipse that will sweep coast-to-coast across America? The lucky people who can get to the line of totality will see a total eclipse of the sun, and be able to view the sun's corona around the outline of the moon.

Whether you can make it or not, print and wear this simple Total Eclipse pendant in honor of our friends the Sun and the Moon.

This model was made in Tinkercad by extruding an SVG image of a previous solar eclipse, then flattening out the edges of the corona with Paraboloids. Here's a link to the model that you can pick apart or edit as you like.

For printing on an FDM/filament machine, use the "halves" file to print in two pieces, and then glue together. This will avoid having nasty supports to remove or build plate ahesion problems. On an SLS/powder printer you can just print the full model directly.

Don't have a printer? Order a print of this model from geekhaus!

title: Wall Dock for J1772 EV Charge Cable

description.text:
I wanted a simple (minimalist) dummy port for the J1772 EV charge cable but kept finding instead full recreations of all the internal plug connections. I did not need those because this is just a holder for the cable while it is not in use. I did not want an overly detailed internal design that would risk a poor fit if all of the individual connectors did not mate properly due to design or print tolerances.

The inside of this connector is mostly empty because nothing needs to be there. It just has the internal channel on the bottom and the latch receiver at the top. That is all that is needed to fit snugly. This was designed with two vertically aligned screw holes so that it can be securely mounted on a wall over a stud.

The only print supports that are required is a very small section for the latch receiver at the very top. Hope you get some use out of it and post your makes and comments.

author: SgaboLab

description.text:
This is a remix of Boxx's awesome Mini Tricopter. I started out adapting his design to a Naze32 style board. I also changed a few things to hopefully strengthen the frame. Along the way I added provision for a buzzer. The V4 frame leaves the bottom flush with the landing skids. This helps with strapping on a battery where the battery butts up against the rear skid. It has built in pads that are removed after printing which help adhere the support material to the print bed .The V4 frame has been printed but I have not installed electronics or flown it yet. Everything else has been printed and flown. Some of the parts may need some fitting but they all work. Everything except the top and tail skid was printed with support material. All pieces were printed in the orientation shown. I have no doubt that this version probably ends up heavier than Boxx's original. But it flys great with the 1806-2300 Dragonfly motors that I am using. I fly it with 3s 1500mah or 1800mah batteries.

I added a few pics. The assembled yellow frame is the V2 with Boxx's original legs.. The black frame with yellow legs is the V4. It also has the remixed legs. The VTX-GPS-Compass top is a project that is currently on the back burner. When I can get back to it it is where I'm headed with this one. I want to fly it with INAV like my bigger Tri but I'm not sure yet how it will work out with everything in such close proximity.

When adding IR repeaters I noted that the XBox One had such a wide sensor area that the repeater itself was not large enough to block the remote signals and was no longer working due to IR duplication coming from the repeater and directly to the remote.

This little print is large enough to block the sensor, provides a spot for the repeater, and stays up due to the stick on the repeater so it is easy to remove should you ever need to. It has worked with a couple different brands of repeaters so it has some good general compatibility.

description.text:
It should be self evident which side of this coin is heads, and which is tails. Note, you will probably want to pick heads, since tails does not seem to be coming up and winning any more. Disclaimer: This is not official coin of the realm, although it should be. These coins are great to give to your kids, to teach them the difference between winning and losing, and being able to spot winners and losers.

But I too am sick and tired of the whining and crying of so called "patriots", pushing their political agendas on here. What I offer is merely my efforts to show the opposite side of the coin, pun intended, and balance the scales.
Just uploaded a photo of the first print I made of the coin. Obviously I need to get my printer dialed in for this coin, as there are a lot of striations in the print.

comments.text: Normally as a courtesy a file that the designer hasn't printed yet or might not print well is marked as a Work in Progress although generally it's a good idea anyway to run any file through software like Netfabb before printing, just in case. A large part of this community is about collaborative efforts on things that aren't finished or haven't been printed yet by anyone so, I do not believe that 3D printing a design before uploading (and proving such with photos of the 3D print) should be a requirement for uploading. Printing out a design does inform the design process and helps the designer improve the design. If you'll pardon the comparison, there is a big difference in how a painting is made depending on whether the artist is using watercolors or thick acrylics and this holds true for designing an object to be 3D printed (vs plastic injection molded).

description.text:
Bracket for a 137 MHz V-dipole antenna following the design found here. I modified the design slightly by removing the screw terminal and mounting solid core copper directly to the aluminum bars.

Included are two different brackets for rods of ~3mm diameter or ~7mm diameter (1/8" or 1/4"), and the lid. Assembly requires 3x M3 bolts and nuts, or zip ties if you don't have the hardware laying around. The mounting tab on the bottom was sized to fit a standard broom handle at ~22mm diameter and includes 4 holes for mounting, but again zip ties will probably work too.

Printed flat down, no supports, 20% infill.

remixed_from.title: Elliptical Gear with no center pivot

description.text: This is a mix of two remixes I saw and decided to combine. It has stronger connection points and a place to put a keychain.

Print the template for the drill spacing. wow this really speeds things along!
The template marks off 32 mm on the ends and 45 mm between the spools

!Print one rack as downloaded and print one that is Mirror or flipped on the Z axis.!

My pvc pipes were 740 mm long.
Be sure to cut the pipes exactly the same length. You may need help putting it together. I personally had the wife hold it together while I drilled a small pilot hole from the back and inserted a short wood style screw for attached the pipes to the rack.

I printed the rods with the slots pointing in the air with no supports. This is why I had the fillet. I printed 40 at a time and they came out wonderful. A slow drilling into the pipes yields a tighter hole and a snugger fit. When your arm is hurting from the 224th hole stay slow! The drill I used was a 7.84 mm or 5/16" Inch. I drilled small pilot holes first, this is why I drilled 224 holes... Ouch!

My rack is 285 mm x 205 mm I included the source files so you could chop the rack down to a smaller print bed.
My rack holds 16 x 7 = 112 spools.

Questions/Comments.. message me.

My printer is modded to print 372 x 214x 200 mm
If you have a Robo 3D you can do it too! Just replace the belt, Rods and print 2 of these

description.text:
Fox and Hen is a board game for 2 people with 20 hens and 2 fox figures

You need:

  • 1x Grundplatte_Groundplate.stl
  • 4x Grundplatte_Sideplate.stl
  • 20x ceramic_rooster_5x5x35mm_hole.stl
  • 2x fox_5x5x35mm_hole.stl
  • 33x Magnet_Stopl_plug.stl (to trap the Magnets in the board)
  • at least 22 Magnets Ø5x3mm for the play figures
    Example: (https://www.gearbest.com/classic-toys/pp_443267.html?wid=21)
  • at least 33 Magnets Ø8x1mm for the board
    Example: (https://www.gearbest.com/classic-toys/pp_443271.html?wid=21)

.

When you push the magnets into the figures, make sure they all have the same polarity - or they will get repelled :)

The magnets at the board are easily changeable/removable thanks to the tight-fitting plugs.

.

------------Fox & Hen------------

.

RULES

The hens start the game. The hens move forward and to the side, but not diagonally or backwards. Allowed is one movement per round. The fox can pull in any direction, straight or oblique to all sides. The fox can "eat" hens. A jump is valid when the fox is standing directly in front of a hen and the field behind it is free. The skipped hen is removed from the game. Serial jumps are allowed. If there is a jumping possibility, the fox must jump. If he does not use them, he is removed from the game. However, he is used again any place when the other fox has jumped (eats a hen). The hens have won when all 9 fields of the target square (the top nine fields of the game board) are occupied with hens or when the fox can no longer pull. The fox has won if there are only 8 more hens in the game or they can not pull.

more detailed rules: https://boardgamegeek.com/thread/1233091/2-foxes-20-hens-how-play-fox-and-henschickens

.

------------Fox & Hen------------

.

  • The magnet-hole.stl is if you want to make custom figures & want to use the same magnet size.
  • at a later date, I will add a top so you can close the "cube"...

.

Yes

0,3mm layers for the board
0,1mm for more detailed figures

Color change on the board; the holes and slits are 1,2mm deep.
1,2mm ÷ 0,3mm layer height = 4 layers (in top color)

After printing the board pieces, lube the joints a bit and force them together. They will snap in.

Game Board printed in FormFutura HDglass (PETG) transparent red & transparent green

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Does not matter what resolution

Does not matter what percentage

Notes:

Since this is my first CAD model I've really made, there are aesthetic imperfections in this model, which do not impact the functionality of the part.

Hi there...

This is the #M4Rover I am currently designing.
I started designing this because I wanted to force myself to learn more about 3D Design, robotics and everything else that's involved in creating a Autonomous rover...
I went thru several old RC-cars witch each had their defects witch in turn stopped my project progression...

Since I have a Ultimaker 2+ readily available I decided to start designing a rover chassis etc. myself. I set myself the challenge not to use much more then 3D printed parts plus M4 Bolts, Nuts & rods, some washers in diff sizes , plus small 3mm to 6mm spring-steel axels for mounting parts.

I set this goal because I want to make it so that others can replicate it without having to order to many specialist parts and all kinds of hard to find screws etc. etc...
The design is mostly based on so-called Rock-Crawlers or -Scalers, hope you like it :)

I appreciate tips and discussion in comments.
Keep following this post, because I will be adding more as he design progresses ;)

Check the grouppage where I will be posting updates ;)
https://www.thingiverse.com/groups/m4rover/topic:19404

title: Bracket for Honeywell 4' LED Linkable Shop Lamps

description.text:
I bought four of these 4500 lumen Honewell LED Lamps on sale at Sam's for around $25 last weekend (normally $35). They're really nice, but they come with chains and I didn't want to hang mine. Using these brackets, they sit beautifully flush with the ceiling and, in my opinion, look much cleaner.

To mount, screw two of these brackets about 3.5 feet apart with at least two 2"+ wood screws. To line them up, I ran them along a stud, screwed down the brackets with one screw in each, briefly pressed a lamp partially into the two brackets to get them straight, and the added a second screw to each. These lamps aren't particularly heavy, but I would recommend that you mount them to a stud. If you can't, definitely use drywall anchors and be careful when attaching/detaching the lamps.

By the way, white would probably look best, but the brackets aren't really that visible from the ground and I didn't have any white ABS (see printing notes below).

title: Thames and Kosmos reinforcement piece for robot arm

description.text:
The Thames and Kosmos Remote-Control Machines set's robot arm has too weak an attachment for the up-and-down (altitude) motion's worm drive--the upper part of the worm screw's axis is attached to a piece that has too much play, and the worm disengages the worm wheel. It would be pretty easy to reinforce this with a 5x hole piece and two studs, but there aren't enough studs in the set.

So I designed a simple reinforcement piece. In the photo, it is the green piece. You might want to adjust the tolerance for your printer. The spacing between the two studs is the same as in a 5X hole piece. Placed diagonally, the piece doesn't fit exactly and hence induces some pressure drawing the worm screw and wheel closer together, which I think is all to the good. But if you want the piece to fit a bit more easily, change piece length from 5 to 5.24.

This piece might be useful for other Thames and Kosmos related purposes.

description.text:
Marble bust of the emperor Hadrian
Period: Hadrianic
Date: ca. A.D. 118 - 120
Culture: Roman
Medium: Marble
Dimensions: H. 18 13/16 in. (47.8 cm)
Classification: Stone Sculpture
Credit Line: Collection of Shelby White and Leon Levy
Accession Number: L.2007.8.2
This artwork is currently on display in Gallery 162
The Metropolitan Museum of Art
http://www.metmuseum.org/Collections/search-the-collections/257689
Scanned with 123DCatch on iPhone 5S on 26 January 2014. Found in Hadrian's villa at Tibur (mod. Tivoli, near Rome) The bust shows Hadrian in the early part of his reign, when his beard was still relatively short and his face had a serene and slightly gay* expression. Romans generally shaved off their beards when they reached maturity in their mid-twenties. Hadrian was the first emperor to continue to wear one and so started a fashion that persisted in imperial portraiture until the time of Constantine in the early fourth century. Hadrian's choice to remain bearded was influenced in part by his love of Greek culture, in which beards traditionally signified wisdom and maturity. *Note: This the MMA's wording, not mine. Presumably it is an old description, and they mean happy.
Not printed yet.

WARNING!!! Looking directly at the sun is unsafe except during the brief total phase of a solar eclipse (“totality”), when the moon entirely blocks the sun’s bright face, which will happen only within the narrow path of totality (https://eclipse2017.nasa.gov/safety (link is external)).

WARNING!!! Aiming a camera at the sun will destroy the imaging sensor it contains if the camera does not have an adequate filter. (https://eclipse.aas.org/eye-safety/optics-filters (link is external)).

However, if you have a solar filter for your camera and are looking for a handy way to aim it at the sun, this might just work for you.

This hotshoe adapter fits on our Canon 7D quite nicely. (You might need to adjust the shoe a bit to make it fit something else. Edit the version that does not include supports.)

When slicing, make sure that features are enabled that detect thin walls. It's called "Detect thin walls" in Slic3r. If you don't, the "screen" won't show up in your print, because it's only 1 pass wide.

When printing, use a lighter colored filament for best results (I prefer white for this). You will be able to see the spot the sunlight makes from either side of the projection screen. (see third photo).

You will want to do this brief setup before the eclipse.
How to use:

  • place the solar viewfinder on the hotshoe bracket on your camera
  • with your camera on a tripod and the filter in place over the lens, aim the camera so that the shadow of the camera is as small as you can make it.
  • with your camera set to as wide an angle view as you can, center the sun in your normal viewfinder. This may take a bit to get right.
  • once you have it centered in the camera's viewfinder, use a black marker and make a circle on the screen of the printed viewfinder around the spot.
  • (DO NOT MARK YOUR CAMERA's viewfinder or screen...just the printed one!)

Now you can quickly get your camera centered on the sun!

Good luck and happy viewing!

title: Meade ETX-60 Telescope Rear Port Cap

description.text:
Had to make a rear port cap for my ETX-60. Threads are apparently 1-3/8 at 22 tpi, the iso tap tool in Tinkered came very close and the part threaded all the way first time. This is only 1 mm thick, the walls are 1.5 mm. The height is 7 mm so the inside depth is about a quarter inch. Location is the straight through rear port under the eyepiece on the ETX-60.

Other options are to remix with more thickness to the base, add a 38 mm disk to the bottom for whatever thickness you want and adjust your fill to fit your needs. The disk is translucent at 1 mm, not much of a worry at night in the dark. But, a thicker back, and/or as I did, wrap in painters tape and spray the inside with rust-oleum flat black primer, it works okay, see photo. Just make sure it dries overnight, the paint will flake off screwing it on, that's better than sticking from wet paint.

I designed this after learning that the original used 0.5 in diameter by 3/16th of an inch thick neodymium disc magnets. A pair of quick coins designed to print very fast, while still having enough thickness to observe the first layer behavior.

title: Prusa MKS Filament Spool Bearing
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: I recently purchased/assembled a Prusa MK2S kit. It is a great printer but it needs a better filament spool holder. I printed and liked the smoothness of the bearing done by EasilyBuild. With that, I set out to design a snap-in bearing that supports different filament spools and attaches to the standard Prusa filament holder.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

25%

The fit is tight by design so that the spool bearing stays firmly attached to the spool at all times. However they are easy to remove and attach to a new spool when required.

For the Airsoft BBs, I purchased Amazon item B000HWPG5A. The cost is low enough that you can print spool bearings for all the filament spools you own.

One of the filament spools (MeltInk) has a recessed hub. The bearing extender allows use of this type of spool.

Installation

When installing the bearing, align with the hub center. Apply even pressure with the lower portion of your palm. TIP — try to miss the spool "ribs". This will allows the bearing to fit tightly without much effort.

Brands

I currently use Hatchbox, MeltInk and esun filaments. Here is a list of what STL files to use with each brand. I will continue to add bearings as I try different filament brands.

Brand STL filename
Hatchbox ... Bearing_H1.stl
esun ... Bearing_E1.stl
MeltInk ... Bearing_M1.stl and Bearing_Extender_M1.stl
Prusa ... Bearing_P1.stl



2017-09-15 Update - Added files for Prusa Filament



Locking feature — insert a small tool to deform the wall and lock in the BBs. Extender — The MeltInk filament spool has a recessed hub on one side. Glue the extender to the spool bearing as shown. Be careful not to add glue to the BBs. With 2000 BBs you can make dozens of spool bearing sets.

description.text:
The "GOLFTUS" Award - Won by Barack Obama for playing the most golf, while in office, of any US President since Eisenhower. Trump may beat Obama's record, but it is too early for anyone to say that. If November 8, 2016 taught Hillary, and the rest of us, anything, it is not to believe that early numbers equal the final outcome. Trump has a long, long way to go to catch up, let alone surpass, Obama's golfing record.

According to Mark Knoller, CBS News White House Correspondent, President Obama, also known as the Golfer-In-Chief (#GOLFTUS), played 64 rounds of golf in 2016 alone, and 333 while President.
https://twitter.com/markknoller/status/815333008991514624?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw

And let us not forget that Obama’s golf weekend with Tiger Woods cost taxpayers more than $3.6 million.
http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/oct/26/obama-golf-weekend-tiger-woods-2013-more-36m/

NOTE: It's not worth posting the ball by itself. It would only wreck your game. Even after 8 years of trying to get it to shoot straight, it would just leave you on the hook, or slice through the value of your 401k. However, I did notice it that once it was anywhere near the green, or even saw green, it would immediately sink the national debt deeper into the hole. It really was the strangest, goofiest ball I have every had the misfortune of playing with.

Special thanks to WADZoQUADZ for his golf ball (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1640986), and Nikita_potemkin1 for his Obama bust (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1384108)

description.text:
The picture and video show prototype. Will put completely 3D printed pictures up soon.

This gripper can pickup foosballs that are in corners or against a wall. If a servo is damaged (on competition day) it should only take a few minutes to swap it out.

Relatively inexpensive to make. The original grippers were build with wood and used a scroll saw. They have been converted to 3D printable objects.

Extras:

  • Two SG90 Servos (should only be a few dollars each)
  • Two coat hangers
  • Handful of small zip ties (from dollar store)

Files are still being tweaked.
Source code for gripper and open scad files can be found at
Open Scad files https://github.com/EricRohlfs/UltrasonicStriker/tree/master/3D-printer-files/foosBallGripper

Python Code : https://github.com/EricRohlfs/UltrasonicStriker/tree/master/code

See SRC1_sonic_striker.py for usage, but Grabber.py is the code you may want to use if you are using a pwm servo hat to drive the servos.

First used in the Virginia Beach STEM Robotics competition 2017.

title: Universal Delta 2020 spool holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Designed to fit all of the spools I have and to snap right on the 2020 extrusions on the top of my printer.
It's a pretty snug fit, so tight that you may have to file away a bit of material.
My advice, as always, is to print the first 2 layers of one of the holders and use that as test fit, you might need to scale up or down on your printer as they're made to print perfectly on mine.
I designed this holder to fit the original rod that came with the printer (Anycubic Kossel).
The adapters have small indents to fit rubberbands to keep them tight.
The two holders have been designed with flat sides so you can lay them flat on the right or left side and print them with no problem.
All of the parts have been printed with a 0.3 layer height, no supports and 10% infill.

Printer:

Anycubic Kossel

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

Lay the holders on one of the sides.
